"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102051","Department of Health","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and social care in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CQC has provided the following information:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>CQC are not currently conducting a review of the prescribing of benzodiazepine.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) collect data on the prescribing of benzodiazepine but this is not collated nationally. The CQC would be alerted to any prescribing trends and outliers during discussions with the CCGs when a GP practice is inspected.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-11-07T12:24:17.6690435Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102051/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102051/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-31","Benzodiazepines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will request that the Care Quality Commission publishes data on trends of GP practices prescribing benzodiazepine.","false","Biography information for Eric Ollerenshaw","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Eric Ollerenshaw","212808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102052","Department of Health","false","2014-11-07","<p>The Consolidated Notification Log 2012/13 record dated 30 September 2011 makes reference to a gamma knife service that might be available sometime in the future at the National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery, part of University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust (UCLH). A gamma knife service is not currently provided by the Trust.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A gamma knife service is provided by an independent provider called Queen’s Square Radiotherapy Centre Limited based at Queen’s Square (a site owned by UCLH).</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-07T13:35:45.6662222Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102052/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102052/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-31","University College Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether University College Hospital London included the provision of gamma knife services at its Queen Square site in its notification log to commissioners before 1 April 2013.","false","Biography information for Tessa Munt","Wells","Tessa Munt","212820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102053","Department of Health","false","2014-11-07","<p>NHS England is currently reviewing the National Cancer Peer Review programme with a view to considering how its success might be extended into other new areas of specialised commissioning. Regardless of the outcome of this review, cancer peer review will continue to play a critical part of any broader peer review programme NHS England may look to introduce.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of visits undertaken by the programme changes based on how many risk visits and how many comprehensive visits are carried out. The highest number of visits completed in any one year since the programme began was 535 in 2012-13, when comprehensive visits to acute oncology were carried out. Generally, between 400 and 450 visits are completed each year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As the programme has moved to risk assessed visits only rather than comprehensive visits (as comprehensive visits to all tumour sites have been completed) the number of visits has reduced; in 2013-14 there were 424 cancer visits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This year, between April 2014 and October 2014, 100 cancer visits and 28 major trauma centre visits have been carried out.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","212807 ; 212809","2014-11-07T13:30:45.6274549Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102053/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102053/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-31","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many cancer-specific reviews were completed by the National Cancer Peer Review Programme team in each financial year since the programme began; and how many cancer-specific reviews are scheduled to be conducted by the National Cancer Peer Review Programme after the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Eric Ollerenshaw","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Eric Ollerenshaw","212810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102054","Home Office","false","2014-11-06","<p>In order to inform the review of the National Referral Mechanism the team has consulted with EU States through the Intergovernmental Consultations on Migration, Asylum and Refugees. The review lead, Jeremy Oppenheim has also met with Danish colleagues to discuss their approach. <br><br>The review team has visited 10 of the contracted service providers in England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. At each visit the team has taken the opportunity to meet victims and discuss their experiences. In addition the team has consulted other organisations that work closely with victims and provide additional services. <br><br>A full list of those who have been consulted will be included in the final report to be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-11-06T16:04:15.1180396Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102054/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102054/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102054/answer/previousversion/26319","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-31","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the National Referral Mechanism review team is taking to consider best practice from other EU member states.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","212828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102055","Home Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>Tackling Modern slavery is a priority for the National Crime Agency, which is committed to improving the co-ordination and coherence of intelligence gathering processes, working with law enforcement partners in the UK and abroad. For example, Europol helped facilitate the arrest of 90 people suspected of human trafficking as part of Operation Archimedes in September this year, and that is why the Government is seeking to rejoin the measure on 1 December. The Modern Slavery Strategy, which will be published shortly, will set out a number of measures to improve the way in which intelligence on modern slavery is gathered, analysed and shared with law enforcement partners.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-11-05T14:27:35.1229774Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102055/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102055/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-31","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to increase co-ordination and coherence in intelligence gathering techniques used in police investigations on human trafficking.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","212829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102056","Home Office","false","2014-11-06","<p>In order to inform the review of the National Referral Mechanism the team has consulted with EU States through the Intergovernmental Consultations on Migration, Asylum and Refugees. The review lead, Jeremy Oppenheim has also met with Danish colleagues to discuss their approach. <br><br>The review team has visited 10 of the contracted service providers in England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. At each visit the team has taken the opportunity to meet victims and discuss their experiences. In addition the team has consulted other organisations that work closely with victims and provide additional services. <br><br>A full list of those who have been consulted will be included in the final report to be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-11-06T16:03:33.3196274Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102056/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102056/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102056/answer/previousversion/26320","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-31","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) victims of trafficking and (b) victim direct service providers have been consulted during the review of the National Referral Mechanism for victims of human trafficking.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","212830"
