"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102010","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-05","<p /> <p>We are absolutely committed to improving performance and will continue to work to further reduce processing times and levels of work outstanding. Both providers have more than doubled the number of assessment reports they are returning to the Department since January, as shown in the official statistics published in September, and the number of decisions made has further increased over recent months.</p><p> </p><p>Departmental statisticians are continuing to develop measures around clearance times and waiting times to ensure they provide a rounded and representative picture of personal independence payment performance, improvement activity and the claimants’ experience. These statistics will be published when they are ready, with the release pre-announced in line with United Kingdom Statistics Authority release protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-05T14:59:19.7221632Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102010/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102010/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-30","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 July 2014 to Question 203682, whether the Government has met its expectation that no-one is waiting longer than 26 weeks for a personal independence payment assessment.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","212537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102011","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-07","<p /> <p>A new web based reporting database was introduced in September 2011 enabling incidents to be reported immediately and more easily.</p><p> </p><p>Violent incidents are recorded as Actual (Physical) Assault incidents. As such, the following Actual Assault incidents recorded each year since January 2011 were:</p><p> </p><p>2011 - 392</p><p>2012 – 646</p><p>2013 – 628</p><p>2014 to September - 372</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-11-07T14:16:20.8308293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102011/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/102011/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-30","Jobcentre Plus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many violent incidents have occurred in UK jobcentres in each year since January 2011.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","212554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106468","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-05","<p>DFID is providing £122 million for humanitarian work in Jordan, providing food, healthcare and other support to thousands of refugees from Syria now living there. In addition, DFID is expanding support to municipal services and education in Jordan, to help the country deal with the impacts of the crisis.</p><p> </p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2014-11-05T15:44:36.784699Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106468/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106468/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-30","Jordan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what refugee relief work her Department is undertaking in Jordan.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","905895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106469","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-05","<p>The British Government is playing a leading role in galvanising international support to tackle Ebola. The Defeating Ebola conference I co-hosted on 2 October generated over £100 million of support, and the Prime Minister’s call to European leaders secured a €1 billion commitment. We will continue to push international partners to do more.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-11-05T15:47:44.4216729Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106469/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106469/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-30","West Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to encourage other developed nations to support efforts to tackle the Ebola virus in West Africa.","false","Biography information for Jim Sheridan","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Jim Sheridan","905898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106470","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Government is advocating for a simple, inspiring, and relevant post-2015 development framework, centred on eradicating extreme poverty. We are actively working with international partners to ensure that access to education and quality of learning is at the heart of the post-2015 focus on education.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-11-05T15:49:30.1865796Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106470/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106470/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-30","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to seek international consensus on post-2015 education goals and targets.","false","Biography information for Annette Brooke","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Annette Brooke","905901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106471","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-05","<p>£42.5 million has been committed by DFID for support to refugees in the region through UN agencies including UNHCR, UNICEF and WFP. DFID offices in the neighbouring countries of Ethiopia, Kenya, Sudan and Uganda are working closely to monitor the situation and provide guidance for future humanitarian support.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-11-05T15:47:15.0824714Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106471/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106471/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-30","South Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to help refugees from conflict in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Sir Tony Baldry","Banbury","Sir Tony Baldry","905896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106472","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-05","<p>Empowering girls and women is a top priority. The Strategic Vision for Girls and Women sets out the ambitious results we will deliver. Significant progress was made at the Girl Summit to tackle Child, Early and Forced Marriage and Female Genital Mutilation.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-11-05T15:48:33.8662056Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106472/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106472/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-30","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to put women and girls at the heart of the UK's development programmes.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","905899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106473","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-05","<p>The UN estimates that 6.4 million people are internally displaced in Syria and a further 1.8 million people internally displaced in Iraq. There are over 3.2 million Syrian refugees in neighbouring countries.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-11-05T15:49:00.8560076Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106473/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/106473/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-30","Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the situation of refugees in Syria and Iraq.","false","Biography information for Mark Hunter","Cheadle","Mark Hunter","905900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101519","Attorney General","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government and the DPP are in agreement that the European Arrest Warrant (EAW) offers the best way of keeping Britain safe, particularly from serious criminals and terrorists.</p><p>The introduction of the EAW has resulted in much faster processing of extradition requests, meaning that we can secure the return of fugitives wanted for serious offending in this country often in a matter of weeks, not many months or even years as was the case under previous arrangements. The Arrest Warrant is also more effective. For example, under the previous regime, the European Convention on Extradition, some Member States can refuse to surrender their own nationals, including France, Germany and Spain, which is not the position in EAW cases. Furthermore, the EAW overcomes problems of time limitation in other countries. It also means that wanted people can now be extradited to face fraud and tax charges, which was not the case before.</p><p>The Government has recently made changes in the way that the EAW is processed through our courts. These changes are designed to offer greater protection to UK citizens and other UK residents against disproportionate requests and the risk of spending unreasonable lengths of time in pre-trial detention abroad. With those changes in place, the Government is convinced that the EAW provides an effective and cost-efficient tool in the fight against trans-national crime, and it is one which prosecutors and other law enforcement professionals are keen to see preserved.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","212406","2014-11-03T17:02:26.1951661Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101519/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101519/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent assessment he has made of the usefulness of the European Arrest Warrant as a prosecutorial tool.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","212405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101520","Attorney General","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government and the DPP are in agreement that the European Arrest Warrant (EAW) offers the best way of keeping Britain safe, particularly from serious criminals and terrorists.</p><p>The introduction of the EAW has resulted in much faster processing of extradition requests, meaning that we can secure the return of fugitives wanted for serious offending in this country often in a matter of weeks, not many months or even years as was the case under previous arrangements. The Arrest Warrant is also more effective. For example, under the previous regime, the European Convention on Extradition, some Member States can refuse to surrender their own nationals, including France, Germany and Spain, which is not the position in EAW cases. Furthermore, the EAW overcomes problems of time limitation in other countries. It also means that wanted people can now be extradited to face fraud and tax charges, which was not the case before.</p><p>The Government has recently made changes in the way that the EAW is processed through our courts. These changes are designed to offer greater protection to UK citizens and other UK residents against disproportionate requests and the risk of spending unreasonable lengths of time in pre-trial detention abroad. With those changes in place, the Government is convinced that the EAW provides an effective and cost-efficient tool in the fight against trans-national crime, and it is one which prosecutors and other law enforcement professionals are keen to see preserved.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","212405","2014-11-03T17:02:26.4052267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101520/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101520/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent discussions he has had with the Director of Public Prosecutions on the usefulness of the European Arrest Warrant as a prosecutorial tool.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","212406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101521","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>The new supercomputer will enable the Met Office to improve the accuracy of its weather forecasts on all timescales. At short-range, for example, the Met Office expects that during the lifetime of the new supercomputer its 24-hour forecast will become as accurate as its 12-hour forecast is now. This will enable the Met Office to provide earlier, more accurate and more detailed warning of severe weather and help the UK to be more resilient and better prepared for high impact events.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-11-06T14:14:04.0754032Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101521/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101521/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-29","Met Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the increased accuracy in weather forecasting arising from the new Met Office supercomputer.","false","Biography information for Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown","South Antrim","Dr William McCrea","212467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101522","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>Data release from ESA missions is governed by agreements approved by all Member States. Release is normally after 6 months, allowing the scientists leading the mission –including many from the UK - to check the integrity of the data and undertake necessary calibrations. This is essential for the data to be scientifically useful.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK will continue to press for the best agreements to maximise the effective use of the data and ensure that images are available as soon as possible to inform the public about these exciting projects.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-11-06T14:20:32.6554358Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101522/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101522/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-29","European Space Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons for the time taken for the general release of data from European Science Agency (ESA) projects; and if he will make future UK contributions to ESA projects conditional on full and immediate release of all data.","false","Biography information for Martin Caton","Gower","Martin Caton","212454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101523","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-06","<p>Information on apprenticeship starts by geography is published in a supplementary table to a Statistical First Release (SFR):</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/364255/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/364255/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls</a></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-11-06T14:16:59.7346036Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101523/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101523/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-29","Apprentices: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many new apprenticeships were created in (a) Cumbria and (b) South Lakeland in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","212460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101524","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-05","<p>This information is not held centrally within BIS and could only be provided at disproportionate cost to the Department.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-11-05T12:52:16.2869561Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101524/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101524/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101525","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-11-04","<p>The mean average cost of a UK Parliamentary by-election, based upon by-elections held between May 2010 and May 2013 is £226,091. By-elections held after this date do not currently have specific costs as claims have not yet been submitted and finalised.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2014-11-04T11:32:08.9863206Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101525/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101525/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101525/answer/previousversion/25862","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-10-29","By-elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, what the average cost to the public purse was of parliamentary by-elections since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","212402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101526","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-04","<p>Many already benefit from a UK zero-rate. So for example, the supply of an ambulance (including an air ambulance) that is purchased with charitable funds is zero-rated for VAT when it is supplied to an eligible body such as an NHS hospital or a charity that provides rescue or first aid services.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-04T16:37:30.7667179Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101526/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101526/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Ambulance Services: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will exempt charitably-funded rapid response vehicles from VAT.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","212407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101527","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-06","<p>The Government has not made an assessment of the effect of income inequality on national wellbeing. However, income inequality remains lower than when this Government came into office.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics estimates that individuals in households with higher incomes report higher life satisfaction and happiness, and lower anxiety. Wellbeing increases fastest in relation to increases income for those on the lowest level of income, and receiving a greater proportion of income from cash benefits is associated with lower wellbeing. The Government’s economic plan is focused on creating jobs and making work pay, while reducing reliance on benefits.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-06T16:19:20.520331Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101527/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101527/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of income inequality on national wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","212385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101528","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-03","<p>Since the financial crisis the government's long term economic plan has provided the foundations for the current recovery, which is now well established. The government has continued to take the difficult decisions needed to secure a stronger recovery for all and build a fairer society.</p><p> </p><p>The latest official labour market figures show that employment in the UK is at its highest ever level, 30.76 million, an increase of 1.7 million since the Coalition entered office. Over the same period the level of redundancies has fallen by 45 per cent.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-03T17:28:07.0630572Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101528/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101528/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the recommendation of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Wellbeing Economics that stable and secure employment for all should be the primary objective of economic policy.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","212387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101529","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-05","<p>This Government has taken a number of major steps to strengthen monitoring and regulation of the banking sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Financial Services Act 2012 put in place two new, properly focussed financial regulators, the Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) - a subsidiary of the Bank of England - the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), as part of a new approach to financial regulation. The new regulators started work on 1 April 2013.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government’s new approach to financial regulation enables the PRA to concentrate on monitoring the health of UK banks to ensure that they are prudently and competently managed and to reduce the risk that the practices of UK banks will lead to serious financial failure. At the same time, the FCA can concentrate on monitoring the practices of UK banks and other financial services businesses in their dealing with ordinary retail customers and in wholesale financial markets, to reduce the risk that the practices in the banking sector are detrimental to consumers or competition, or threaten the integrity of financial markets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On 12 June 2014, the Government announced the Fair and Effective Markets Review, which is a joint review by HM Treasury, the Bank of England, and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) into the way wholesale financial markets operate. The Government is determined to take action to help restore trust and integrity and to ensure that the highest standards are expected of those who operate in these markets. It is important that this is done in a way that preserves the UK’s position as the global financial centre for many of these markets. The Review published its consultation document “How fair and effective are the fixed income, foreign exchange and commodities markets?” on 27 October, and the Government looks forward to the review’s final recommendations in June 2015.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-11-05T16:50:46.5086619Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101529/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101529/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he has taken to monitor practices in the banking sector.","false","Biography information for Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown","South Antrim","Dr William McCrea","212470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101530","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-04","<p>A record of Ministerial meetings is published and updated periodically on the government website. For Treasury Ministers, this is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2014-11-04T16:50:54.4383164Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101530/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101530/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings the Exchequer Secretary has had with representatives of the tobacco industry since his appointment.","false","Biography information for Sir Kevin Barron","Rother Valley","Kevin Barron","212455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101531","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-05","<p>The UK is at the forefront of multilateral action through the G8, G20, European Union and OECD to tackle this issue of corporate tax avoidance. The UK used its Presidency of the G8 to successfully build international support for this work.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Work is now underway at the OECD, in the form of the Base Erosion and Profit Shifting (BEPS) project. The BEPS project is the most comprehensive reform of the international tax rules with the aim of ensuring that multinational enterprises pay their fair share of tax, in the jurisdictions where their economic activity is located. The project has 44 participant countries, 21 of which are within the EU.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At the UK’s Lough Erne summit in June 2013 the G8 leaders confirmed their support for the ongoing G20/OECD work.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At their September 2013 summit in St Petersburg, the G20 Leaders fully endorsed the ambitious and comprehensive BEPS Action Plan set out over 2014 and 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The first phase of the BEPS project is now complete, with participants reaching agreement on seven reports which have been produced by the OECD and endorsed by G20 Finance Ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The G8 called on the OECD to develop a common template for multinationals to report profit and tax information to tax authorities to help assess risks. This work was included in the BEPS Action Plan (action 13) and was one of seven outputs achieved in 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Subsequently, the UK announced that it would be the first of 44 countries to formally commit to implementing the newly agreed BEPS output of a country-by-country reporting template.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Discussions are ongoing in G20 Finance Minister’s and ECOFIN meetings to ensure that the momentum of the BEPS project is maintained, so that the project is completed successfully and on time.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further to the BEPS project, international work with G20 and EU counterparts is ongoing with the Automatic Exchange of Information policy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK put tax transparency at the heart of its presidency of the G8, calling for the creation of a new global standard on automatic tax information exchange to tackle offshore tax evasion. The new global standard was developed by the OECD and agreed in July 2014. At the March European Council leaders committed to implement the standard in the EU through agreement of the amended Administrative Co-operation Directive, which they aim to agree by the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In total 92 countries and have now committed to implement the new global standard, with the first information exchanged no later than 2018. This includes all EU Member States, all of the UK’s Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories with a financial centre and the majority of the world’s financial centres. Of these countries and jurisdictions, 51 have already signed an international agreement to implement the standard.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","212453","2014-11-05T17:58:27.155082Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101531/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101531/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with his EU counterparts about measures to reduce tax avoidance; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","212452"
