"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101607","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-06","<p /> <p>Universal Credit has been available online for new claims from Single people from April 2013, has been available to Couples from June 2014 and will be available to Families by the end of the year.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-06T17:08:10.999354Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101607/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101607/answer","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101607/answer/previousversion/25890","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he expects Jobcentre Plus to deploy an IT solution for the calculation of universal credit for those other than single people; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","212412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101608","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-04","<p>Information on actual and forecast expenditure can be found in the following table “Outturn and forecast: Budget 2014” which can be found via the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-expenditure-and-caseload-tables-2014</a></p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-04T17:27:59.0124496Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101608/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101608/answer","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101608/answer/previousversion/25889","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's projected expenditure on (a) disablity living allowance and (b) personal independence payment is in each year up to 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","212399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101609","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-06","<p>DWP has well developed processes for testing IT systems prior to roll out. This encompasses a range of testing phases, which includes user and business testing cycles. Testing is done through a range of expert practitioners who have experience in managing and delivering DWP business.</p><p> </p><p>UC IT systems used these testing methodologies to ensure expert practitioners and staff including front line work coaches were a key part of test cycles.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The number of front line work coaches involved at each stage of testing varies and as such we are unable to give an exact figure.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","212396","2014-11-06T16:41:45.8715997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101609/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101609/answer","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101609/answer/previousversion/25888","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many front line job centre advisers will take part in user acceptance testing of the IT systems developed to facilitate the delivery of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","212398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101610","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p>There has been no formal conclusion to the infringement proceedings brought by the European Commission against the Government of the UK with regard to the application of the ‘Past Presence Test’ for certain disability benefits.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T15:54:22.6475885Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101610/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101610/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Social Security Benefits: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a conclusion has been reached on infringement proceedings generated by the European Commission against the Government of the United Kingdom, with regard to the application of the 'Past Presence' test for disability benefit purposes as it affects ex-patriate citizens of the United Kingdom now resident in other EU member states; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Roger Gale","North Thanet","Sir Roger Gale","212388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101611","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-04","<p /> <p>DWP uses a standard methodology to design and test business processes and IT systems. These have been developed over years of best practice using external expertise and in-house practitioners who have many years of experience in delivering DWP business. These best practice methods have been used to test that the Universal Credit IT systems and business processes are complete and fit for purpose prior to roll out.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","212490","2014-11-04T17:17:16.8301323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101611/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101611/answer","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101611/answer/previousversion/25886","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what metrics were used to determine whether the IT systems developed to facilitate the delivery of universal credit pathfinders were fit for purpose.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","212395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101612","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-06","<p /> <p>DWP has well developed processes for testing IT systems prior to roll out. This encompasses a range of testing phases, which includes user and business testing cycles. Testing is done through a range of expert practitioners who have experience in managing and delivering DWP business.</p><p> </p><p>UC IT systems used these testing methodologies to ensure expert practitioners and staff including front line work coaches were a key part of test cycles.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The number of front line work coaches involved at each stage of testing varies and as such we are unable to give an exact figure.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","212398","2014-11-06T16:41:45.7681223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101612/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101612/answer","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101612/answer/previousversion/25887","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many front line job centre advisers took part in user acceptance testing of the IT systems developed to facilitate the delivery of universal credit pathfinders.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","212396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101613","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-03","<p /> <p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Universal Credit Programme has and continues to employ PRINCE 2 methodology among other development programmes in the delivery of IT and Business Services. Alongside this the Programme also adheres to the Government Digital Service standards required for Digital Projects and Programmes, ensuring that external assurance of the Programme considers the robustness of the programme management controls being applied.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-11-03T17:43:49.2567674Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101613/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101613/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-29","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the programme management of universal credit made use of the Prince2 methodology.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","212397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101614","Attorney General","false","2014-11-19","<p>The CPS defendant case outcome records include an allocation of a reason for each unsuccessful outcome, including the number which did not proceed because of victim issues. These records are centrally collated under the following twelve Principal Offence Categories.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Homicide</p><p> </p><p>Offences against the person</p><p> </p><p>Sexual offences</p><p> </p><p>Burglary</p><p> </p><p>Robbery</p><p> </p><p>Theft and handling</p><p> </p><p>Fraud and forgery</p><p> </p><p>Criminal damage</p><p> </p><p>Drugs offences</p><p> </p><p>Public order offences</p><p> </p><p>Motoring offences</p><p> </p><p>All other offences</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"2014-11-19T12:38:15.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101614/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101614/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, for which offences the Crown Prosecution Service routinely monitors the number and proportion of cases that fail because of victim issues.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","212435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101615","Attorney General","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) maintains a central record of the numbers of defendants and the outcome of prosecution proceedings, divided into twelve Principal Offence Categories, including ‘Fraud and Forgery’.</p><p> </p><p>The category of ‘Fraud and Forgery, includes offences prosecuted by way of the Fraud Act 2006, fraudulently evading income tax, VAT, excise duty or national insurance, bankruptcy offences, money laundering, forgery or using a false instrument and obtaining property, services or pecuniary advantage by deception.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows, in each of the last five calendar years, the number of defendants prosecuted and finalised, in Crown Courts in Wales, where the Principal Offence was categorised as ‘Fraud and Forgery’.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Total Prosecutions</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td><p>181</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>163</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>185</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>180</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>149</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Data Source: CPS Management Information System</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Principal Offence Category is assigned at the end of a prosecution to indicate the most serious offence with which a defendant is charged at the time of finalisation. It is not possible to disaggregate the outcomes of individual offences, such as fraud, without undertaking a manual search of case records which would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This table does not include those cases prosecuted by the DWP prosecution teams that merged with the CPS in 2012, as the DWP Cardiff team prosecutes cases in Crown Courts in England, as well as Wales. It is not possible to provide a breakdown of cases prosecuted solely in Wales without incurring a disproportionate cost.</p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"2014-11-05T15:53:50.8523458Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101615/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101615/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","Fraud: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many fraud prosecutions the Crown Prosecution Service has brought in Crown Courts in Wales in each of the last five calendar years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","212436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101616","Attorney General","false","2014-11-04","<p>Offences of breaching immigration law may be prosecuted by way of Section 25 of the Immigration Act 1971 (assisting unlawful immigration to a European Union Member State) or by way of Section 1 of the Criminal Law Act (conspiracy).</p><p>The offence created by Section 25 of the Immigration Act 1971 encompasses both the offence of assisting illegal entry (whether by smuggling someone in a vehicle or by providing false documents for presentation at a port) or by assisting someone to remain by deception (for example, by entering into a sham marriage) which facilitate a breach of the immigration laws. Conspiracies to facilitate breaches of immigration law are charged by way of Section 1 of the Criminal Law Act 1977.</p><p>The records held by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) indicate the number of offences charged, in which a prosecution commenced at magistrates’ courts for assisting unlawful immigration or conspiracy. However it is not possible to disaggregate which of these offences relate to sham marriages rather than other immigration law breaches without reviewing individual case files which would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"2014-11-04T14:31:53.3374111Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101616/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101616/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","Marriage of Convenience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many prosecutions the Crown Prosecution Service has brought on breaches of immigration law arising from sham marriages in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","212437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101617","Attorney General","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Serious Fraud Office (SFO) has a core budget to investigate and, where appropriate, prosecute the most serious and complex cases of fraud, bribery and corruption, and some exceptionally large cases will arise that require additional resources. However it is not in the public interest to specify in detail what resources the SFO intends to dedicate to each case.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"2014-11-05T15:56:51.8028748Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101617/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101617/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","Tesco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what reports he has received on whether the Serious Fraud Office will apply for additional funding from HM Treasury to finance its investigation into Tesco.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","212438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101618","Attorney General","false","2014-11-05","<p>The following table contains the available costs information for internal staff or client surveys which the Law Officer’s Departments commissioned during 2013 and 2014. These costs were all incurred with Survey Monkey.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Subscription costs – Survey Monkey</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Department</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong> </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Treasury Solicitor’s Department</p></td><td><p>£272</p></td><td><p>£296</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attorney General’s Office</p></td><td><p>£249</p></td><td><p>£249</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate</p></td><td><p>£203</p></td><td><p>£151</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Serious Fraud Office</p></td><td><p>£299</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not centrally record the number and costs of all surveys and focus groups across the organisation, and to determine this would involve contacting all CPS Areas to manually check their records over the two year period, which would represent a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"2014-11-05T15:52:26.1888336Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101618/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101618/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much the Law Officers' Departments spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101619","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-03","<p>Senior Officials from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) Yorkshire Humber North East Office have been assigned to assist UK Coal following their interest in applying for government funding to extend the operation of the two remaining deep mines until the end of 2018. These officials met with UK Coal on 10 October and are now working with them to help prepare a case for Government support. The company fully understands that this is the first phase of a complex and challenging process before the government submits a state aid case to the European Commission.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-03T16:24:19.4246192Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101619/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101619/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-29","UK Coal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many full-time equivalent officials of what grade in his Department have been assigned to assist UK Coal in the drafting of a state aid bid.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","212484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101620","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office, the Deputy Prime Minister's Office and the Office of the Leader of the House are integral parts of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Spend incurred by my department on focus groups and surveys does not fall into a dedicated account code and can therefore only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","212497","2014-11-05T17:40:05.8644216Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101620/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101620/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much was spent by (a) 10 Downing Street, (b) the Deputy Prime Minister's Office, (c) the Office of the Leader of the House and (d) the Cabinet Office on (i) focus groups and (ii) surveys in (A) 2013 and (B) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101621","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-05","<p>The net impact on UK contributions to the EU of revisions to the UK GNI under ESA95 could not have been calculated without the relevant information across all Member States.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-05T17:56:19.0228798Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101621/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101621/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions his officials had with the Office for National Statistics between January and October 2014 on provision for backdating of payments of European contributions to accord with the European Statistics Agency reconciliation of the European Budget under ESA95.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","212527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101622","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-05","<p>Under the Own Resources Decision of 7 June 2007, ESA 95 is the current statistical base for calculations of Member State contributions to the EU Budget.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>ESA2010 will not become the statistical base for Member State contributions to the EU Budget until the new Own Resources Decision, agreed in May 2014, comes into force following ratification by all EU Member States.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-05T17:56:56.5887704Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101622/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101622/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the progress of arrangements to secure compliance with the requirements of ESA 2010 with respect to future calculation of the UK's European Budget contribution.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","212528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101623","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-05","<p>The European Commission are responsible for calculating Member State contributions to the EU Budget using data provided by Eurostat who collate and validate the data from Member States’ national statistical institutions, including for the UK the Office for National Statistics.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister has stated, HM Treasury will now assess the data in exhaustive detail to check how the statistics were arrived at and the methodology that was used.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-11-05T17:56:49.7411434Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101623/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101623/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the accuracy of the European Statistics Agency's calculation of UK's contribution liability in respect of the European Budget under ESA 95 between 27 May and 13 October 2014.","false","Biography information for Stewart Hosie","Dundee East","Stewart Hosie","212529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101624","HM Treasury","false","2014-12-09","<p>In answer to the first part of your question, the department is unable to provide spend on focus groups. The data is not held centrally, and to attempt to collect the information would engage the disproportionate costs threshold.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As to the second part of your question, I can confirm that the total spend on surveys by the department in 2013, and up to 31 October 2014 is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year April 13-March 14</p></td><td><p>Financial Year April 14-March 15</p></td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>10,604.40</p></td><td><p>10,604.40</p></td><td><p>Spend</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This compares to £25,203.50 in 2008/09.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-12-09T16:57:54.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101624/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101624/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101625","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-11-17","<p>The information is not centrally held in the form requested and could only be provided at disproportionate cost, although I am not aware of significant expenditure.<br><br>As outlined in the answer of 25 March 2014, <em>Official Report</em>, House of Lords, Column WA99, we have undertaken qualitative research into the experience of tenants who might take up the Right to Buy, to help inform ways of increasing the take-up of the Right to Buy.</p><p> </p><p>We have significantly reduced spending on surveys compared to the last Administration– for example, by abolishing the £4 million Citizenship Survey and the £5 million Place Survey.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-11-17T11:47:13.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101625/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101625/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101626","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-11-06","<p>The information requested can be found in the Local Government Ombudsman’s annual report and accounts, which are presented to Parliament each year, and which are available online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.lgo.org.uk/publications/annual-report/" target="_blank">http://www.lgo.org.uk/publications/annual-report/</a></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-11-06T17:19:28.5847116Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101626/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101626/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-10-29","Local Government Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funding is allocated to the Local Government Ombudsman; how many staff the Ombudsman employs; and how many enquiries were received by the Ombudsman in (a) 2012-13 and (b) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Joan Walley","Stoke-on-Trent North","Joan Walley","212525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101627","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-05","<p>This information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-11-05T14:21:55.1824618Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101627/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101627/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101628","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-24","<p>The amount spent on focus groups and surveys is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-24T17:13:31.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101628/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101628/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101628/answer/previousversion/26466","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101629","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-10","<p>It is not possible to provide details of how much is paid in each age range to recipients of the Allowance for a Lowered Standard of Occupation and the Unemployability Supplement because details of such expenditure are not held in age groupings, and could be provided only at disproportionate cost. However, for financial year 2013-14, a total of £33 million was paid to recipients of the Allowance for a Lowered Standard of Occupation and £37 million was paid to recipients of the Unemployability Supplement.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-10T17:27:29.4921015Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101629/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101629/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101629/answer/previousversion/26467","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-29","War Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much in total is paid to claimants of the War Pensions Scheme in each age group claiming (a) the Allowance for a Lowered Standard of Occupation and (b) the Unemployability Supplement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","212520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101630","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-06","<p>It is not possible to provide details of how much on average is paid to recipients of the Allowance for a Lowered Standard of Occupation and the Unemployability Supplement because details of such expenditure are not held in age groupings, and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>However, for financial year 2013-14, an average £60 per week was paid to recipients of the Allowance for a Lowered Standard of Occupation and an average £110 per week was paid to recipients of the Unemployability Supplement.</p><p><em>In line with Defence Statistics' Rounding Policy, all figures of five or more have been rounded to the nearest 5.</em></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-11-06T17:45:50.2445195Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101630/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101630/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101630/answer/previousversion/26468","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-29","War Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much on average is received each week by claimants of the War Pensions Scheme in each age group who claim (a) the Allowance for a Lowered Standard or Occupation and (b) the Unemployability Supplement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","212521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101631","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-06","<p>There are currently 30 UK Service personnel and two Foreign and Commonwealth Office civilians serving in the European Union Training Mission in Mali (EUTM Mali). There are two UK Service personnel serving in the United Nations Multidimensional Integrated Stabilisation Mission in Mali (MINUSMA). Of these 34, five speak both English and French.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-11-06T17:31:08.0821435Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101631/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101631/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101631/answer/previousversion/26461","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-10-29","Mali","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) HM service personnel and (b) civilians have been seconded by the UK Government to (a) MINUSMA and (b) the EU Training Mission in Mali; and how many such personnel speak both English and French.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugh Bayley","York Central","Hugh Bayley","212440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101632","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office, the Deputy Prime Minister's Office and the Office of the Leader of the House are integral parts of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Spend incurred by my department on focus groups and surveys does not fall into a dedicated account code and can therefore only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","212513","2014-11-05T17:40:05.6456741Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101632/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101632/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much his Office spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101633","Department for Education","false","2014-11-05","<p>There was no centrally coordinated or funded focus group or survey activity in 2013.</p><p>In 2014, The Department for Education spent £14,016 and £15,720 on two separate sets of centrally coordinated focus groups. Respectively, these were to support delivery of important campaigns aimed at increasing both the number of young people studying Science, Technology, Engineering and Maths (STEM) subjects, and also the number of two-year-olds receiving their entitlement to 15 hours of free childcare or early learning. We also subscribed to an online survey facility (Survey Monkey) at a cost of £299 for the year.</p><p>To establish whether other areas of the Department have undertaken activity in this area would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb",,"2014-11-05T15:08:15.3062525Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101633/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101633/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101634","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Department spent:</p><p> </p><ul><li>£1,647,021 on surveys and £34,630 on focus groups in 2013;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>£2,613,726 on surveys and £76,925 on focus groups in 2014.</li></ul><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2014-11-05T15:58:04.5384548Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101634/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101634/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101635","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-04","<p>The 14<sup>th</sup> Onshore Oil and Gas Licensing Round closed for applications on the 28<sup>th</sup> October 2014, and we have received 95 applications covering in total 295 blocks. (A block for these purposes is a 10x10 km area.) Some blocks were applied for by more than one applicant.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-04T15:49:37.6931897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101635/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101635/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101635/answer/previousversion/25893","Biography information for Matt Hancock","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-29","Fossil Fuels: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many bids were received in the 14th licensing round for onshore oil and gas.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","212485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101636","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-11-04","<p>The assessment of the applications received is in hand, but it is too early to say how soon the necessary work can be completed. We hope to be able to announce licence offers in the early part of 2015.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-04T15:47:31.2118368Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101636/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101636/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101636/answer/previousversion/25891","Biography information for Matt Hancock","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-10-29","Fossil Fuels: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when he intends to announce the awarding of licences arising from the 14th Onshore Oil and Gas Licensing round.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","212486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101637","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-05","<p>Due to the way spend is recorded in the Department’s finance systems, this information can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-11-05T15:42:49.2096639Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101637/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101637/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much her Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101638","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-05","In 2013 the Foreign and Commonwealth Office spent £637,195.60 on surveys and recorded no spend on focus groups. In 2014 £336,146.22 was spent on surveys and £87,110.23 on focus groups. This work covered issues such as data on UK businesses investing abroad and consular research, including traveller behaviour.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-11-05T14:48:30.9973593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101638/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101638/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101639","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-03","<p>Along with Parliamentary Question 211845, answered on 29 October 2014 (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/</a>?) and correspondence from Members of Parliament and Peers, we have also received letters from members of the public on this issue. <br> <br> My right hon. and noble Friend the former Minister of State, Baroness Warsi met Anwar Ibrahim during her visit to Malaysia in April and raised his case with senior members of the Malaysian government. Our High Commission in Malaysia has discussed the matter with Malaysian ministers and officials on a number of occasions. The former Minister of State again met Anwar Ibrahim during the latter’s visit to the UK in June. <br> <br> Anwar Ibrahim’s appeal against his conviction is being monitored closely by officials from our High Commission in Malaysia who are attending court hearings alongside other local diplomatic missions. We are aware of allegations that the case is politically motivated. As the case is not yet concluded, it would be inappropriate to comment further.</p><p> </p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2014-11-03T13:08:39.9922025Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101639/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101639/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-29","Malaysia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received on the conviction against Anwar Ibrahim, Leader of the Opposition of Malaysia; if he will raise his conviction for sodomy with his Malaysian counterpart; and if he will assess whether the charge and conviction of Anwar Ibrahim is a case of political persecution.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","212489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101640","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>Bosnia and Herzegovina was invited to initiate their first cycle of a Membership Action Plan in 2010 on the condition that they register their immovable defence property. This condition has not yet been fulfilled.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), together with his counterparts from NATO Allies, met NATO’s aspiring members, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, Macedonia and Montenegro, on 4 September 2014 during the NATO Summit in Wales to discuss their progress towards joining the Alliance.</p><p>At the Summit, the Allies reaffirmed their continued support for Bosnia and Herzegovina’s eventual membership and encouraged them to meet the established conditions on which their next steps towards NATO depend.</p><p>The United Kingdom strongly supports NATO’s Open Door policy on enlargement and welcomes the membership aspirations of all the countries currently seeking to join the Alliance.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-11-05T15:05:55.7593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101640/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101640/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-29","Bosnia and Herzegovina","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his NATO counterparts on the possibility of offering a Membership Action Plan for Bosnia and Herzegovina; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","212442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101641","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-05","<p>The first cycle of Macedonia’s Membership Action Plan was initiated in 1999 and in 2008 the Allies agreed that an invitation to join NATO would be extended as soon as a mutually acceptable solution to the issue over its name has been reached with Greece within the framework established by the UN. This condition has not yet been fulfilled.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commomwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), together with his counterparts from NATO Allies, met NATO’s aspiring members, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Georgia, Macedonia and Montenegro, on 4 September 2014 during the NATO Summit in Wales to discuss their progress towards joining the Alliance.</p><p>At the Summit, the Allies reaffirmed their continued support for Macedonia’s eventual membership and encouraged them to meet the established conditions on which their next steps towards NATO depend.</p><p>The United Kingdom strongly supports NATO’s Open Door policy on enlargement and welcomes the membership aspirations of all the countries currently seeking to join the Alliance.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-11-05T15:03:12.459081Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101641/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101641/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-29","Macedonia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his NATO counterparts on the possibility of offering a Membership Action Plan for the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","212443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101642","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-03","<p>The Government has made clear to the Nigerian authorities, at all levels, that whilst we support Nigeria’s fight against terrorism, we do not condone human rights violations. We have urged Nigeria to respond constructively to credible reports of human rights violations and to launch independent investigations. During his meeting with the Nigerian Foreign Minister in Abuja on 3 September, my Hon Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge MP), the Minister for Africa, underlined the importance we attach to the respect for human rights and the safeguarding of the civilian population.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-11-03T14:23:33.4663558Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101642/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101642/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-29","Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Nigerian counterpart on alleged human rights abuses by the Nigerian military; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Mr Gareth Thomas","212481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101643","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-03","<p>The UK is working closely with Nigeria, its neighbours and other international partners to tackle Boko Haram, including to find victims of abduction. The UK is providing a substantial package of support, including training and advice to Nigerian military units that will be deployed against Boko Haram, surveillance assets and intelligence expertise. We have also committed £1 million to the UN Safe Schools Initiative, designed to promote a safer environment for children in north east Nigeria to receive their education.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2014-11-03T14:10:40.9011582Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101643/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101643/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-29","Boko Haram","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking with his international counterparts to co-ordinate the rescue of girls and women kidnapped by Boko Haram; what steps he is taking to help prevent further such abductions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Mr Gareth Thomas","212480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101644","Department of Health","false","2014-11-05","<p>There are no official statistics on the number of vacancies for any profession or group in the National Health Service following the decommissioning of the Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) vacancy survey in 2011.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The HSCIC only provides statistics relating to locum consultants in clinical radiology that have a fixed term or permanent contract with an organisation. The latest monthly workforce statistics for 31 July 2014 shows that there are 19 full time equivalent locum consultants in clinical radiology in the NHS in England.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Radiologists also work in the private and independent sectors but the numbers are not collected centrally.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-11-05T15:13:08.7171951Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101644/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101644/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","Radiology: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many consultant radiologist posts in NHS trusts are (a) vacant and (b) covered by locums.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","212519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101645","Department of Health","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Department has not assessed the effect of mindfulness based interventions on National Health Service staff in respect of wellbeing, stress, levels of care and compassion, absence and productivity, the management of which are the responsibility of individual employers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the Francis report (www.midstaffspublicinquiry.com/), the Department has also commissioned NHS Employers to support trusts improve the emotional and mental health and wellbeing of their staff, staff engagement and organisational development. This includes the production of training packages for the management of mental health issues, a behaviour change toolkit and an emotional wellbeing pathway to help NHS staff access support and interventions for themselves and their colleagues.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-11-05T15:11:31.9601187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101645/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101645/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","NHS: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of mindfulness-based interventions on NHS staff in terms of (a) wellbeing levels, (b) stress levels, (c) levels of care and compassion, (d) staff absence and (e) productivity.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","212522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101646","Department of Health","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Department does not collect this information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are aware of a report by the Nuffield Foundation (2013), <em>Social trends and mental health: Introducing the Main Findings</em>, which said that there has been an increase in the proportion of young people reporting frequent feelings of depression or anxiety. This figure doubled between the mid 1980’s and 2005. For boys aged 15/16, rates were found to increase from approximately 1 in 30 to 2 in 30. For girls they increased from approximately 1 in 10 to 2 in 10.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department, with key partners, is in the process of commissioning a new prevalence survey of children and young people’s mental health to provide an accurate picture of mental health in children and young people.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"2014-11-05T16:07:48.3610701Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101646/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101646/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","Depression: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what change there has been in the average age of the onset of depression in young people over the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","212523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101647","Department of Health","false","2014-11-05","<p>We recognise that drinking alcohol and drug use does place significant strain on the National Health Service, but there are both ethical and practical reasons not to seek payment from patients. The founding principle of the NHS is that services are free of charge, available to all on the basis of need, not ability to pay. It is funded accordingly, from general taxation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-05T15:40:41.9778304Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101647/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101647/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of charging for NHS services required because of injuries caused by alcohol or drug misuse.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","212524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101648","Department of Health","false","2014-11-05","<p>In 2014-15, NHS England has allocated £177,027 for promoting its own staff wellbeing as well as an additional £10,000 for flu prevention.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-11-05T15:12:23.1862758Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101648/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101648/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","NHS: Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding NHS England makes available for promoting staff wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","212439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101649","Department of Health","false","2014-11-03","<p>It is envisaged that the vast majority of future provision of National Health Service services will be by NHS bodies, including Multispecialty Community Providers. Further details about how NHS England intend to support areas wishing to develop these providers will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2014-11-03T17:43:50.9216782Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101649/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101649/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","NHS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to his oral contribution of 23 October 2014, Official Report, columns 1044-5, on Five Year Forward View, if he will ensure that any Multispeciality Community Providers are NHS providers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","212491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101650","Department of Health","false","2014-11-05","<p>The Department has funded focus groups and surveys, but extracting the amount of spend could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"2014-11-05T15:07:50.0384589Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101650/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101650/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much his Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101651","Home Office","false","2014-11-03","<p>We are unable to answer this question as our financial accounting information system does not identify the cost of focus groups or surveys.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-11-03T14:55:45.8078734Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101651/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101651/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-29","Public Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department spent on (a) focus groups and (b) surveys in (i) 2013 and (ii) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","212503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101652","Home Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The most recent Arrest Warrant issued by the UK to Ireland for terrorism-related offences was on 29 August 2013, with the subject surrendered in February 2014. <br><br>There are currently two outstanding Arrest Warrants for terrorism-related offences that were issued by the UK to Ireland.<br><br>The Government of Ireland made clear in a letter dated 4 September 2014 from the Irish Justice Minister to the Home Secretary that should the UK fail to opt in to the package of 35 criminal justice measures on 1 December 2014, there is no guarantee that the Irish courts would preserve the validity of outstanding Arrest Warrants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","212488","2014-11-10T15:59:42.8806097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101652/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101652/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101652/answer/previousversion/25732","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-29","European Arrest Warrants: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the last European Arrest Warrant was issued by the UK to the Republic of Ireland in relation to an offence or offences related to terrorism.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","212487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101653","Home Office","false","2014-11-10","<p>The most recent Arrest Warrant issued by the UK to Ireland for terrorism-related offences was on 29 August 2013, with the subject surrendered in February 2014. <br><br>There are currently two outstanding Arrest Warrants for terrorism-related offences that were issued by the UK to Ireland.<br><br>The Government of Ireland made clear in a letter dated 4 September 2014 from the Irish Justice Minister to the Home Secretary that should the UK fail to opt in to the package of 35 criminal justice measures on 1 December 2014, there is no guarantee that the Irish courts would preserve the validity of outstanding Arrest Warrants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","212487","2014-11-10T15:59:43.1149835Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101653/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101653/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101653/answer/previousversion/25735","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-29","European Arrest Warrants: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many European Arrest Warrants issued by the UK to the Republic of Ireland for terrorism-related offences remain outstanding.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","212488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101654","Home Office","false","2014-11-17","<p>Following investigations, significant steps have been taken to identify, locate and remove those who have fraudulently obtained visas through abuse of ETS. <br><br>The Home Office publishes quarterly transparency data which shows the total number of individuals who have been removed as a result of their involvement in the Educational Testing Service fraud. The most recent published data covers the period up to 30 June 2014 and can be found at: <br><br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-august-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-august-2014</a> <br><br>As at 30 June, the Home Office had made more than 1800 refusal and removal decisions, carried out almost 800 enforcement visits, detained over 300 <br>individuals and removed over 90.<br><br>We are unable to break the number of individuals who have been removed into sub groups based on the institution of study as this runs the risk of making those individuals identifiable. In addition to this the data that would be required to make the requested breakdown is not available from one source and would incur disproportionate costs to gather it manually. <br><br>As I stated to the House on 24 June, the Home Office will provide regularupdates to the House. These updates will be provided as part of the <br>regular publication of data on the department’s work on borders and immigration.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","212476 ; 212477","2014-11-17T16:26:54.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101654/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101654/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101654/answer/previousversion/25719","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-29","Overseas Students: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many students of have been deported from UK universities and colleges as a result of investigations into Educational Testing Service since February 2014.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","212478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101655","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-05","<p>In the last 12 months the Civil Aviation Authority has prosecuted two operators of remotely piloted aircraft for breaches of the Air Navigation Order in England. Both prosecutions resulted in convictions.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-11-05T12:35:06.9889791Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101655/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/101655/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-29","Unmanned Aerial Vehicles: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many prosecutions have been brought against operators of unmanned aircraft in (a) England and Wales and (b) Northern Ireland in the last 12 months; how many such prosecutions were successful; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","212518"
